{"id":"math/0601421","submitter":"Peter Bubenik","authors":"Peter Bubenik","title":"Cell attachments and the homology of loop spaces and differential graded\n  algebras","comments":"108 pages. This is my Ph.D. thesis written under the direction of\n  Paul Selick at the University of Toronto (accepted: July 2003)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AT","license":null,"abstract":"  The cell-attachment problem, perhaps first studied by J.H.C. Whitehead around\n1940, asks one to describe the effect of attaching one or more cells, on the\nalgebraic invariants of a topological space. This thesis studies the effect of\ncell attachments on loop space homology. It generalizes previous work by D.\nAnick on spherical 2-cones, and S. Halperin, J.-M. Lemaire and others on inert\nattaching maps.\n  It is assumed that the loop space homology of the base space is torsion-free.\nTwo classes of attaching maps are introduced: free and semi-inert attaching\nmaps. For these cases, the loop space homology is calculated as a module and as\nan algebra, respectively, and is shown to have a surprisingly simple form.\nThese results are also presented in terms of extensions of differential graded\nalgebras.\n  The second part of the thesis uses Adams-Hilton models and the previous\nresults to prove that the loop space homology of certain CW complexes is\ngenerated by Hurewicz images. This can sometimes be used to show that the loop\nspace of a finite complex is, after localizing away from finitely many primes,\nhomotopy equivalent to a product of spheres and loops on spheres.\n  A lemma, which may of independent interest, generalizes the Schreier\nproperty, which states that a Lie subalgebra of a free (graded) Lie algebra is\nalso a free Lie algebra.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Jan 2006 20:38:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
